Hyperlink class extends Canvas. My assumption has been that 'getFont' should always return a valid font even if 'setFont(null)' has been used. What does 'Argument no valid' mean - that Font resource has been disposed or something else?

I have a few environment variables on my Linux system which span multiple lines. They are bash shell functions exported from ~/.bash_profile as follows:

function example_func()
{
    echo First line
    echo Second line
    echo Third line
}
export -f example_func

In the output of printenv, they will indeed appear in multiple lines:

example_func=() {  echo First line;
 echo Second line;
 echo Third line
}

However, if I start a process from Eclipse and use the Environment tab to append some new environment variables, the original multi-line ones are truncated (only the first line of them remains in the target's environment).

The problem seems to be in LaunchManager.cacheNativeEnvironment, which incorrectly assumes that environment variables may not contain line breaks.

fixed in HEAD, using bash's pattern for exported functions:

[name]=() {
[body]
}

see LaunchManager#cacheNativeEnvironment

